SERVICEEXPLAIN: Wish professors and lecturers don't use cursive writing style because I am an international student. I am not taught to read cursive hand writing style from CAEL, and IELTS.
RESPONSIVEEXPLAIN: Please avoid using cursive writing style.
RAPPORTEXPLAIN: Professor Steve Shirtliffe, I was at his class one time. I had the impression that he preferred making jokes instead of providing knowledge. SAFETYEXPLAIN: Wish students have more option to eat foods. Subway in kinesiology closes too fast. Marquis wouldn't serve supper during summer.
FOCUSEXPLAIN: Sending an email isn't specialized service for international students. International students office should be more active; operating various events to allow domestic students to feel close with foreign students. Cultural difference, personal difference should be taken into account, however, my learning method is different than discussing Canadian education system, Lab instructor Ellen Misfeldt once treated me so bad; she thought I was selfish. Participating in discussion always distracts me; it's who I am...
CURRICULAEXPLAIN: Instructors should not use cursive hand writing; I cannot read as an international student. Some of assessments would be done by graduate school students; every one has different opinion, marking is pretty opinion based. If I have generous marking person, I would end up with good marks. If I have strict marking person, I would ended up with okay score. Marking should be done by only one person. Regarding time. wished students have more classes afternoon. Many classes tend to schedule in early morning. It's pretty difficult to get the campus at rush hour, snowing time, out of town.
INSTRUCTORSEXPLAIN: Lecturer Burton Urquhart does not tend to provide feedback in timely manner. Many instructors don't want a change. Coming in class room and reading materials were the way they were taught. It does not have to be the same way to future generation. We need a change. Canadian society and university tend to keep working on the same flow. If it is needed, instructors are needed to be changed instead of giving them tenure to not look for adventure and challenge.
COURSESEXPLAIN: There are not many distance learning classes provided from U of S. During summer, students usually don't have many choices to take courses. The tuition fee for international students is too expensive and it is getting more and more. THERE ARE NOT SUFFICIENT SCHOLARSHIPS For INTERNATIONAL STUDENTS. Most of bursary and scholarships are focused at landed immigrants and canadian citizen.
SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: U of S faculty and instructors tend to be conservative. I don't know if the job offering flow is fair; few excellent score students are selected from professor to recommend a job offer. It is fair to every one? I disagree with it. If there is a job position, there should be a chance to take resumes and get through all the interviews regardless of hierarchical references.

RAPPORTEXPLAIN: Not all faculty are friendly and courteous.

INFRASTRUCTUREEXPLAIN: Some of the learning spaces can be a bit uncomfortable because of the winters because they are not always warm. This causes a lot of students to get sick and not feel comfortable in the schools spaces.
RESPONSIVEEXPLAIN: There have been many times in which I have emailed faculty members or administrators and have not received information or an email for weeks, even up to a month.
INSTRUCTORSEXPLAIN: There are some instructors that do care about the students and engage in learning but others do not. I feel as though we should hire instructors that also care about the students well-being or at least train the already hired professors to understand that some students need extra assistance in learning or need to understand mental health issues as it affects many students.

SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: The experiences I had at the U of S are not fully captured in this survey and that was why I responded disagree and neutral on this page. The programs are not clearly spelt as you come in. It will be the student that will be asking the department "what courses should I register this term" and all those type of question. Students need to have a blueprint of their program as they come in so that the person would make up his/her mind on how to go about the program. May be it is my department alone that is doing it here but I am very disappointed in this aspect at the university

SERVICEEXPLAIN: I never used any of the services provided by ISSAC
SAFETYEXPLAIN: Options for better health and dental insurance would be a bonus
COURSESEXPLAIN: Despite good marks (I got into vet school, so they're pretty good) and commitment to community engagement, I have received no scholarships, college of agriculture could do more for international undergraduates. We shall see if this improves now that I am a permanent resident.

Tuition and fees are rising with the stipend provided for graduate students does not change at all. As opposed to the U.S.A, graduate students does not have to pay for tuition and fees and health insurance is also provided. Here at USASK you have to pay $895 monthly for tuition and fees if you choose the installment plan. After deduction of rent, phone and food you find yourself with no savings at all. You can work 20 hrs per week that's an option but how can you do that when you are overwhelmed with research.

SERVICEEXPLAIN: Faculty members seem to be busy with their internal problems, which they did not spend adequate time for graduate students. INSTRUCTORSEXPLAIN: Many materials posted on the Blackboard are not in good quality, I mean they are scanned in a poor manner and quality. There are not ample visual - audio materials, which accommodates the audio-visual students

SERVICEEXPLAIN: Have never used issac to know

INFRASTRUCTUREEXPLAIN: Outdoors could be more cleaner after winter (especially sand, stones)
INSTRUCTORSEXPLAIN: Not all instructors provide feedback at all, which is bad for learning

INFRASTRUCTUREEXPLAIN: Library doesn't have enough space for all students... they should be more close to natural environment Also theft is the biggest issue

SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: I love U of S just because of my supervisor. He is realy cool and knowlegeble. Otherwise, the quality of teaching in engineering department is really low.

SERVICEEXPLAIN: Faculty member in general are helpful, But I have had two different professors that were not trustworthy and did not hold up to their so-called ideals. and they did not provide any help at all which was disappointing. mainly a professor called Christopher Dutchyn.
CURRICULAEXPLAIN: I have crossed upon many professors in the computer science major which did not follow their curriculum. Also, anyone who takes a course with Christopher Dutchyn, does not get any learning material as he says that he should not tell provide us with slides as we are university students.

INFRASTRUCTUREEXPLAIN: Some of the lecture halls can be TOO warm in winter. The "airplane room" made me sick it was so hot in there. News of emergency situations/threats could be relayed over PAWS as well at the moment of occurrence so that one can avoid dangerous areas.
SAFETYEXPLAIN: Security and Safety are the only thing I am unsure of. As last year there was some sort of threat toward faculty members and it was not made known until after the police had dealt with the issue. Also, there is no real security on campus that I have noticed other than alarms/alerts/cameras. It would be nice to have some options available to prevent crime/danger rather than just to help after something happens. Also sexual assault on campus makes me nervous to participate in any social events on campus.
INSTRUCTORSEXPLAIN: Honestly depends on the instructor. I have had some who don't provide many good learning opportunities and some who's primary focus is on the students' learning.
COURSESEXPLAIN: As far as fees/tuition I think they are unfairly high. Education is so important to any community yet there is a lack of access to the education due to the costs involved. Many young people start University to gain a well-paying job only to realize they will either not afford the tuition or be in debt to loans for the next 20 years. International students have it far worse as far as the costs go. Not only is tuition higher but so is the living costs of being in a new country. When a Canadian born student like myself needs to work 2 jobs during the school year in order to make ends meet, I cannot imagine what that would be like in a country away from my emotional support like family and friends.
SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: I would enroll in the University again, but I would work to get done my degree the fastest and cheapest that I could.

INFRASTRUCTUREEXPLAIN: hard chairs in the older class rooms need to be upgraded; older buildings need upgrading.

SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: there should be equity and fairness in treating international students. i.e. no double fees; They should not be required to purchase books i.e.free e-books and free assignments; free academic papers; more tutoring help; extra time given in writing exams as english is difficult; exam questions should be easy to read and written in simple terms etc.; and marked tests should be returned to students to learn their mistakes; markers should provide more, better feedback etc

SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: I am really enjoy my experience in U of S, but if I have choice to over again I prefer to choose a more modern city.

Q6O: College of Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies
SERVICEEXPLAIN: The residence services department put a lot of pressure on students, especially those living in student residence. Sometimes asking students to renew their rent several months ahead of time. The department also seem not to have any human face towards students during move ins and move outs periods. Residence contracts can expire several days before the end of a calender month, yet students cannot even stay an extra day witout being charged. I think student residence services have to look at these things again.
RESPONSIVEEXPLAIN: Most faculty members do not always respond promptly to student written essays and assignments. I have heard a lot of my colleagues complain of having to wait even months before they get feedback on papers they submit to their supervisors or instructors.
SAFETYEXPLAIN: I have noticed little challenges with few security issues, which has to do with theft. Many of my room mates got their bicycles stolen both on campus and at the student residence. The bicycles were even locked, but the locks were cut and the bicycles taken away.
CURRICULAEXPLAIN: The course curricula is also overloaded for graduate students. Many PhD students have to take many courses before even doing their qualifying and comprehensive exams in addition to presenting and defending their proposals before even applying for ethics approval. Comparatively to most European universities, all the premilinary courses and exams take a chunk of the student time before students even begin with the research component of their.  degrees
COURSESEXPLAIN: Tuition and tuition fees are a challenge to some of us, especially the spring/summer tuition fees. Most international students do not have good funding, therefore, it is a challenge paying tuition in summer when one is not attending classes or even have any serious academic work to do.
There are too many scholarships that you can't access as an international student and considering the difficulties of differential rates and lack of access to loans that is extremely unfair.

INFRASTRUCTUREEXPLAIN: Every student is not driving or having own car so there should be some source of connection to different departments in winter like I never knew about underground tunnels before to walk through in winter. Also bus service should be provided for all students whether the course is on campus or off campus. Orientation should be common for all new comers giving complete info on infra structure of campus.
SERVICEEXPLAIN: Faculty members all are not the same. On campus and off campus students do face some problems. My courses are online and I never get chance to see instructors having so many doubts to clear about the content assignments as emails the only source is not sufficient. Being new to the place its extremely tough to gather information without guidance of proper instructions. I have struggled with my course to find all details as instructor was new and sessional. For online courses at least some way of approach meeting should be provided.
RESPONSIVEEXPLAIN: Instead of emails face to face contact with instructors or faculty members work better as on phone a lot of time and patience is required to be on hold.
RAPPORTEXPLAIN: University is best but some faculty members not all should be supportive and provide equality for all students inspite being so busy in their schedule.
SAFETYEXPLAIN: Though online courses do not require you to visit campus but still health insurance should be provided for all students. I didn't get it though in my email it was mentioned you will be provided with dental and health insurance because of my online study. Its not fair.
FOCUSEXPLAIN: Happy with other services at the University.
CURRICULAEXPLAIN: Curriculum is well planned but it should be provided to students in advance not a day before your course starts. The assignments included are too many one in each week.
INSTRUCTORSEXPLAIN: Not all the instructors provide opportunities to ask questions or provide details on the course materials. Some of them are new who don't have much idea about online courses  and esp language instructors make students struggle more.
COURSESEXPLAIN: The fee structure for online and on campus is approx.same. Online programs should be charged less fee as students are not visiting the campus or getting any other benefits.
SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: Overall. I have struggled and learned many things on my own. Happy about association what all students have formed on our country celebrating all festivals. Some discount other facilities should be available for disabled students whether its Canadian or International. More scholarships or educational loan facility should be available for International students..

SERVICEEXPLAIN: Some faculty members (who are naturalized Canadians) do not treat international students (from the same country faculty member was born or once lived) the same as Canadian students. Those faculty members also pass personal comments, in the absence of an effective complaint mechanism, the international student ends up staying silent. In my experience, the University Leadership is over cautious (about taking action against those faculty members) and worries that they will be seen as anti to those faculty members who were not born in Canada, but that is not right. If a faculty member is not adhering to the values of Canada and the University, there should be strict action for that. Many faculty members even end up putting the international students in their basements/ properties as renters, which is another form of exploitation, there must be a strict policy against any direct or indirect financial gains by faculty members from the international students.

SERVICEEXPLAIN: ISSAC support staff/administrators care about students, and are very trustworthy and helpful.
FOCUSEXPLAIN: Office and access hours tend to be convenient, however, in the case of a weekend or holiday it may be difficult for students to access help when needed. (First weekend + Labor Day after Move-In date was very difficult for new students to access services when needed most)
COURSESEXPLAIN: Instead of providing a lot of students with small guaranteed entrance scholarships it could be better if the university created bigger scholarships for international students who need it more - not just those with exceptional academic performance (since those are already covered)
SATISFACTIONEXPLAIN: "Brand name reputation" is high in Canada but not in other countries

FOCUSEXPLAIN: Office hours could could be improved to facilitate students who are in calss/need to in office from 8am to 4:30pm a little better.

CURRICULAEXPLAIN: As a visiting research student, I don't have a scheduled for classes.
